In <Jan.8.10.57.51.1992.8483@dumas.rutgers.edu> masticol@dumas.rutgers.edu (Steve Masticola) writes:


>If Gemstar had superenciphered their codes with a private key, and
>used a public key to decipher them, it would not have been so easy to
>break the codes. 

With only 10^8 codes, brute force (as was done for the first 10^4 codes)
might be feasible.

>What I don't know is whether such a scheme would yield short
>ciphertext for short plaintext. Does anyone have more expert
>knowledge?

Not likely; if it did, it could only be a modified substitution
cypher.
